I hope we catch some fish soon. </i>

2
00:01:12,771 --> 00:01:14,102
<i> Me too. </i>

3
00:01:14,173 --> 00:01:16,698
- Okay, help me wind.
- Wind back?

4
00:01:16,775 --> 00:01:20,211
Can we turn this one?
Slowly.

5
00:01:20,279 --> 00:01:22,645
Slowly, slowly,
slowly, slowly.

6
00:01:22,715 --> 00:01:25,548
- I am doing it slowly.
- Okay, you got it.

7
00:01:25,618 --> 00:01:27,586
Oh, Matty, look!

8
00:01:27,653 --> 00:01:30,121
- You see that big boat out there?
- Mm-hmm.

9
00:01:30,189 --> 00:01:35,991
<i>She is the prettiest boat on Whidbey
Island. That's the Morning Star. </i>

10
00:01:36,061 --> 00:01:39,155
Someday when you're big enough,
I'm gonna teach you how to sail.

11
00:01:39,231 --> 00:01:41,995
<i>- It's the best thing there is, sailing.
- Better than fishing?</i>

12
00:01:42,067 --> 00:01:45,400
Yup.
But you know what, kiddo?

13
00:01:45,471 --> 00:01:48,440
- I don't think I want you to grow up.
- Why?

14
00:01:48,507 --> 00:01:50,498
<i>What if you grow up
and marry some beautiful girl?</i>

15
00:01:50,576 --> 00:01:54,512
- Who's gonna go sailing with me then?
- Dad.

16
00:01:54,580 --> 00:01:56,480
Not a chance.

17
00:02:01,820 --> 00:02:03,754
Thank you so much.

18
00:02:12,398 --> 00:02:15,492
<i>Nick. Uh, we need to talk. </i>

19
00:02:15,568 --> 00:02:18,594
Always happy to talk to you, Rudy.
Hey, Warren.

20
00:02:18,671 --> 00:02:21,663
Did you get that notice
from First Seattle today?

21
00:02:21,740 --> 00:02:24,038
Yeah. Yeah, as a matter of fact, I did.

22
00:02:24,109 --> 00:02:26,373
- Good.
- Then you know.

23
00:02:26,445 --> 00:02:30,438
- We've got a real problem.
- First Seattle is not a problem.

24
00:02:30,516 --> 00:02:33,178
These martinis are a problem.
Do you mind?

25
00:02:33,252 --> 00:02:36,346
<i>- Not at all.
- Where were we? Right, First Seattle.</i>

26
00:02:37,590 --> 00:02:40,559
- Mommy?
- Hey, kiddo.

27
00:02:40,626 --> 00:02:44,084
<i>- How's it going?
- Hand off.</i>

28
00:02:46,298 --> 00:02:48,732
- Oh, you sack of potatoes.
- Ay-yi-yi.

29
00:02:48,801 --> 00:02:51,099
Have you been carrying him
around the whole party?

30
00:02:51,170 --> 00:02:53,297
- Yeah.
- We're never gonna marry you, Angie.

31
00:02:53,372 --> 00:02:58,071
Mm, yes. Picasso.

32
00:02:58,143 --> 00:03:00,304
Blue Period.

33
00:03:00,379 --> 00:03:03,507
<i>The artist's name is Kandinsky. </i>

34
00:03:03,582 --> 00:03:05,516
Wassily Kandinsky.

35
00:03:05,584 --> 00:03:10,078
He was German, of Russian extraction,
1866 to 1944.

36
00:03:10,155 --> 00:03:12,783
And by the way,
Picasso's Blue Period was figurative...

37
00:03:12,858 --> 00:03:15,053
and ended in 1904.

38
00:03:15,127 --> 00:03:19,393
And these watercolors
are abstract, done in 1911.

39
00:03:23,369 --> 00:03:26,497
Picasso.

40
00:03:29,041 --> 00:03:31,669
Everyone pipe down.
I'm about to give a speech.

41
00:03:31,744 --> 00:03:34,679
<i>Thank you for coming.
I always say the sign of a good party... </i>

42
00:03:34,747 --> 00:03:37,079
is when I'm having a better time
than anyone else, but...

43
00:03:37,149 --> 00:03:39,379
now is the time when you're
expected to ante up...

44
00:03:39,451 --> 00:03:41,749
for drinking all my liquor,
and eating all my food...

45
00:03:41,820 --> 00:03:46,450
and spilling tomato sauce
on my couch, Bobby Long.

46
00:03:46,525 --> 00:03:50,120
<i>-  Ooh...
- What, you didn't think I saw you?</i>

47
00:03:50,195 --> 00:03:53,062
- Oh, he's insufferable.
- I know it.

48
00:03:53,132 --> 00:03:56,124
<i>Now, we are here to raise a vast sum
of money for the Small Frye School. </i>

49
00:03:56,201 --> 00:04:00,160
<i>So, while you are reaching
for your checkbooks... </i>

50
00:04:00,239 --> 00:04:02,639
it gives me great pleasure to
introduce Mrs. Rebecca Tingley...

51
00:04:02,708 --> 00:04:04,903
<i>our totally ravishing... </i>

52
00:04:04,977 --> 00:04:07,969
<i>and completely adorable Headmistress. </i>

53
00:04:11,483 --> 00:04:13,644
Mr. Parsons, thank you.

54
00:04:13,719 --> 00:04:16,483
<i>First of all, I'd like
to start by introducing... </i>

55
00:04:16,555 --> 00:04:20,787
- a few members of my staff to you today.
- Oh, God.

56
00:04:20,859 --> 00:04:23,589
I give you our dedicated teacher
and Head of Admissions...

57
00:04:23,662 --> 00:04:25,596
Miss Angela Green.

58
00:04:25,664 --> 00:04:28,497
Yea!

59
00:04:28,567 --> 00:04:33,004
Me!

60
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:45,844
What are you thinking about?

61
00:04:45,918 --> 00:04:48,853
Was I always as rude as I am now?

62
00:04:48,921 --> 00:04:51,185
Absolutely.

63
00:05:00,332 --> 00:05:04,530
Hi.
Come have a seat.

64
00:05:13,879 --> 00:05:16,643
Angela, do you think we ought
to break the news to her?

65
00:05:16,715 --> 00:05:19,843
I suppose it's better she hears it
from us than from someone else.

66
00:05:19,918 --> 00:05:22,284
She's not gonna be
happy about it.

67
00:05:22,354 --> 00:05:24,481
What's up, guys?

68
00:05:25,557 --> 00:05:27,491
Close your eyes.

69
00:05:27,559 --> 00:05:30,494
Close 'em.

70
00:05:30,562 --> 00:05:34,498
Okay, now, stand up.

71
00:05:34,566 --> 00:05:37,126
Keep 'em closed.

72
00:05:44,276 --> 00:05:46,540
<i>Now, Libby,
what is your favorite thing?</i>

73
00:05:46,612 --> 00:05:49,137
- Me?
- Not even close.

74
00:05:50,983 --> 00:05:53,474
All right, open.

75
00:05:56,155 --> 00:05:58,089
<i>I heard Sean Gittman
was thinking of selling. </i>

76
00:05:58,157 --> 00:06:00,091
<i>I made him an offer... </i>

77
00:06:00,159 --> 00:06:02,093
and he agreed to let us
take her out for the weekend.

78
00:06:02,161 --> 00:06:04,527
And if you like it, it's yours.

79
00:06:04,596 --> 00:06:07,156
<i>- If I like it?
- Mm-hmm.</i>

80
00:06:07,232 --> 00:06:09,723
<i>Honey, we can't afford that. </i>

81
00:06:09,801 --> 00:06:12,099
<i>When have I ever let that
get in my way? Come on. </i>

82
00:06:12,171 --> 00:06:14,162
Huh?

83
00:06:14,239 --> 00:06:16,070
What about Matty?

84
00:06:16,141 --> 00:06:18,541
I'll take care of him.
We'll have a great time.

85
00:06:20,179 --> 00:06:22,704
<i>You hate to sail.</i>

86
00:06:22,781 --> 00:06:25,011
I can learn.

87
00:06:27,286 --> 00:06:29,811
Huh?

88
00:06:53,912 --> 00:06:57,439
<i>Generally, wine like this
needs time to breathe... </i>

89
00:06:57,516 --> 00:07:00,679
but I don't know,
I don't think we should...

90
00:07:00,752 --> 00:07:02,686
wait.

91
00:07:03,789 --> 00:07:05,723
I don't see land.

92
00:07:08,694 --> 00:07:11,424
So where is it?

93
00:07:11,496 --> 00:07:13,964
Alaska's over that way,
Japan is straight ahead...

94
00:07:14,032 --> 00:07:16,762
and Australia's
somewhere to the left.

95
00:07:16,835 --> 00:07:18,769
Where would you like to go?

96
00:07:18,837 --> 00:07:20,737
Bed.

97
00:07:20,806 --> 00:07:23,673
That can be arranged.

98
00:08:08,587 --> 00:08:11,420
We should do this more often.

99
00:08:11,490 --> 00:08:14,516
What do you mean?
Buy expensive sailboats?

100
00:08:14,593 --> 00:08:17,562
If this is what happens,
I'll buy another one tomorrow.

101
00:08:17,629 --> 00:08:22,225
No, go away, just the two of us...

102
00:08:22,301 --> 00:08:24,599
with nobody else around.

103
00:08:29,141 --> 00:08:31,234
I'll drink to that.

104
00:08:41,753 --> 00:08:43,687
Nick?

105
00:08:48,060 --> 00:08:50,790
Nick?

106
00:08:52,798 --> 00:08:55,858
Oh, my God.
Nick?

107
00:08:59,338 --> 00:09:01,272
<i>Nick?</i>

108
00:09:13,952 --> 00:09:16,921
Nick? Ni...

109
00:09:16,988 --> 00:09:20,549
<i>Oh, my God. </i>

110
00:09:35,974 --> 00:09:37,908
Nick?

111
00:09:46,351 --> 00:09:50,378
Nick!
Nick!

112
00:09:52,290 --> 00:09:55,282
<i>Nick!
Oh, my God. </i>

113
00:09:56,828 --> 00:10:00,992
Oh, my God.
Oh, my God.

114
00:10:01,066 --> 00:10:03,000
Nick?

115
00:10:04,870 --> 00:10:07,600
<i>Morning Star, this is the Coast Guard. </i>

116
00:10:07,672 --> 00:10:10,937
<i>Put the knife down,
ma'am, and step away. </i>

117
00:10:11,009 --> 00:10:13,671
I- I don't...
I don't know...

118
00:10:13,745 --> 00:10:17,579
I don't know...
where my husband is!

119
00:10:17,649 --> 00:10:20,243
...search for local businessman...

120
00:10:20,318 --> 00:10:23,889
Nick Parsons, who disappeared
in these waters off Whidbey Island.

121
00:10:31,663 --> 00:10:34,257
All right, tie it off.

122
00:10:36,368 --> 00:10:39,667
<i>- Hey, Cutter.
- Hey, Tom. What have you got for me?</i>

123
00:10:53,385 --> 00:10:56,479
<i>- Anything?
- No.</i>

124
00:10:56,554 --> 00:10:59,250
Cutter, please don't let them give up.
He's very strong.

125
00:10:59,324 --> 00:11:02,657
- Libby. L-Libby.
- He's a very strong man.

126
00:11:06,498 --> 00:11:09,831
The raft and life preservers
are all on board.

127
00:11:09,901 --> 00:11:14,634
These guys,
they tracked the wind, currents...

128
00:11:15,840 --> 00:11:20,300
Nothing.
The water temperature overnight...

129
00:11:20,378 --> 00:11:22,312
was 51 degrees.

130
00:11:22,380 --> 00:11:25,144
That's cold. That's really cold.

131
00:11:26,952 --> 00:11:29,648
- Cutter, I can't breathe!
- Just put your head down.

132
00:11:29,721 --> 00:11:31,916
Yeah, that's it.
Deep breaths.

133
00:11:31,990 --> 00:11:34,015
Big breaths.

134
00:11:37,062 --> 00:11:39,587
Shh.

135
00:12:01,987 --> 00:12:05,753
Mommy, look!

136
00:12:16,101 --> 00:12:18,695
Hi, kiddo.

137
00:12:20,572 --> 00:12:22,506
Hey, Bobby.

138
00:12:24,876 --> 00:12:27,208
Hey, Libby.

139
00:12:27,278 --> 00:12:30,111
Um, well, Cutter, he, uh...

140
00:12:30,181 --> 00:12:32,547
<i>He asked me to come by
and talk to you, you know. </i>

141
00:12:32,617 --> 00:12:35,677
<i>Just, um...
Not as an attorney, just as a friend. </i>

142
00:12:38,056 --> 00:12:40,854
The inquest was held this morning,
and they reviewed all the evidence...

143
00:12:40,925 --> 00:12:44,952
and Nick, uh, well,
he's officially been declared dead.

144
00:12:46,998 --> 00:12:50,161
<i>Now, Libby, they, um... </i>

145
00:12:50,235 --> 00:12:53,932
<i>they've determined it was
a "wrongful death, and you... </i>

146
00:12:54,005 --> 00:12:58,601
Oh, Jesus, you... You're being
formally charged with his murder.

147
00:12:58,676 --> 00:13:00,610
<i>I am here to advise you. </i>

148
00:13:00,678 --> 00:13:03,408
<i>Make no statements
whatsoever to the sheriff. </i>

149
00:13:05,683 --> 00:13:07,776
<i>I'm sorry, Libby. </i>

150
00:13:12,424 --> 00:13:14,824
<i>Cutter!</i>

151
00:13:14,893 --> 00:13:17,589
Not in front of my kid, okay?

152
00:13:45,556 --> 00:13:48,889
I'm sorry, Libby.
Uh, the judge denied us bail.

153
00:14:00,037 --> 00:14:02,164
Can Angie keep looking after Matty?

154
00:14:04,374 --> 00:14:08,538
<i>Good. Okay, uh... </i>

155
00:14:08,612 --> 00:14:12,548
<i>- Let's look at this, see what we can do.
- Bobby.</i>

156
00:14:12,616 --> 00:14:14,846
<i>Here's what
I think happened. </i>

157
00:14:16,520 --> 00:14:19,284
I had some wine, okay?

158
00:14:19,356 --> 00:14:21,756
And I fell asleep.
It must have been the sun.

159
00:14:21,825 --> 00:14:26,660
<i>And maybe Nick was trying
to cut a snagged line or something... </i>

160
00:14:26,730 --> 00:14:30,257
because the knife...

161
00:14:30,334 --> 00:14:32,529
from the galley
was on deck.

162
00:14:32,603 --> 00:14:36,733
And-And maybe the boat
pitched or something...

163
00:14:36,807 --> 00:14:38,775
and he cut himself.

164
00:14:38,842 --> 00:14:42,107
And he tried to come downstairs.
He tried to come below...

165
00:14:42,179 --> 00:14:44,875
to wake me up.

166
00:14:56,894 --> 00:14:58,953
I quit these things
when I met Nick.

167
00:15:00,297 --> 00:15:03,061
It'll be all right.
I promise you.

168
00:15:04,868 --> 00:15:08,599
<i>So. Why don't we take a look
at this First Guarantee Life?</i>

169
00:15:10,240 --> 00:15:13,368
Now. You both bought
life insurance policies...

170
00:15:13,443 --> 00:15:16,469
from the company
around four months ago.

171
00:15:18,782 --> 00:15:22,582
- And you are the beneficiary.
- I'm his wife.

172
00:15:22,653 --> 00:15:25,053
Libby, you know this policy is
worth two million?

173
00:15:25,122 --> 00:15:28,489
Nick wanted to make sure that if
anything happened to him, we'd be okay.

174
00:15:28,559 --> 00:15:31,585
The jury may feel there's a difference
between "okay" and $2 million.

175
00:15:31,662 --> 00:15:34,062
<i>They may see it as a motive. </i>

176
00:15:34,131 --> 00:15:36,565
- Is that what they're saying?
- No, no one is saying that.

177
00:15:36,633 --> 00:15:41,263
- I don't think we have to be concerned...
- That I killed Nick for money?

178
00:15:45,242 --> 00:15:47,233
I know we had some problems,
and Nick worried...

179
00:15:47,311 --> 00:15:49,245
- but we were okay!
- Libby!

180
00:15:49,313 --> 00:15:52,510
Two of his investors
were suing him for embezzlement.

181
00:15:52,583 --> 00:15:55,108
First Seattle issued a lien on
all of his real estate properties...

182
00:15:55,185 --> 00:15:57,449
your personal possessions...

183
00:15:57,521 --> 00:15:59,580
Now, Nick's death means
all these problems disappear...

184
00:15:59,656 --> 00:16:04,093
<i>behind a corporate shield,
leaving you with $2 million. </i>

185
00:16:07,197 --> 00:16:10,792
- Do you think I killed him?
- The first rule of being a lawyer.

186
00:16:10,867 --> 00:16:12,926
What we think doesn't matter.

187
00:16:13,003 --> 00:16:15,301
It matters to me.

188
00:16:18,075 --> 00:16:21,203
No. Of course.
I don't think you killed him.

189
00:16:24,948 --> 00:16:28,008
<i> Petty Officer Young,
what was the condition... </i>

190
00:16:28,085 --> 00:16:31,851
<i>of the Morning Star's marine band radio
when you had a chance to inspect it?</i>

191
00:16:31,922 --> 00:16:34,220
The handset cord
had been cut.

192
00:16:34,291 --> 00:16:37,158
<i>And as you initially
approached the sailboat... </i>

193
00:16:37,227 --> 00:16:40,025
what did you see?

194
00:16:40,097 --> 00:16:42,861
Mrs. Parsons
was holding a knife.

195
00:16:46,236 --> 00:16:51,139
I show you State's exhibit...
number four.

196
00:16:51,208 --> 00:16:53,301
Uh, Mayday. Mayday.

197
00:16:53,377 --> 00:16:55,242
<i>This is the Morning Star. </i>

198
00:16:55,312 --> 00:16:57,906
<i>State your emergency, Morning Star.</i>

199
00:16:57,981 --> 00:16:59,972
<i>I've been stabbed. </i>

200
00:17:00,050 --> 00:17:03,451
<i>I'm bleeding, uh...
Oh, Jesus. </i>

201
00:17:03,520 --> 00:17:06,250
<i>My na...
My name's Nicholas Parsons. </i>

202
00:17:06,323 --> 00:17:09,918
<i>-  State your position.
- I don't know, man. </i>

203
00:17:09,993 --> 00:17:15,192
<i>Three miles northwest of,
uh, of Whidbey Island, I guess. </i>

204
00:17:15,265 --> 00:17:18,894
Oh, God! Oh, God!

205
00:17:18,969 --> 00:17:22,234
<i> Mrs. Parsons, you've heard
the testimony presented to this court... </i>

206
00:17:22,305 --> 00:17:27,538
<i>and your explanation is that somebody
must have come aboard the Morning Star. </i>

207
00:17:27,611 --> 00:17:33,516
- That's right.
- Let's consider all the possibilities.

208
00:17:33,583 --> 00:17:35,983
Maybe a band of pirates.

209
00:17:36,053 --> 00:17:39,386
Or aliens!
Did aliens murder your husband?

210
00:17:39,456 --> 00:17:43,017
No. Aliens weren't beneficiaries in...

211
00:17:43,093 --> 00:17:45,459
<i>- your husband's life insurance policy.
- Objection.</i>

212
00:17:45,529 --> 00:17:47,622
<i>- Your Honor, the prosecutor...
- Overruled.</i>

213
00:17:47,698 --> 00:17:50,599
- I told you what happened.
- Yes, you did.

214
00:17:50,667 --> 00:17:54,068
- You told us that you were asleep.
- Yes.

215
00:17:54,137 --> 00:17:57,436
<i>Maybe you were sleepwalking
when you stabbed your husband. </i>

216
00:17:57,507 --> 00:17:58,496
<i>Objection. </i>

217
00:17:58,575 --> 00:18:01,100
<i>Is Miss Halliwell questioning the
witness, or making a closing argument?</i>

218
00:18:01,178 --> 00:18:05,877
- Withdrawn.
- I didn't kill my husband!

219
00:18:05,949 --> 00:18:07,940
I loved my husband.

220
00:18:11,655 --> 00:18:16,524
Bobby, I did not
kill my husband!

221
00:18:16,593 --> 00:18:19,653
You have to believe me.

222
00:18:35,011 --> 00:18:37,411
<i>I'm-I'm sorry, Libby. </i>

223
00:18:39,216 --> 00:18:42,447
It's not your fault, Bobby.

224
00:18:52,796 --> 00:18:55,094
I want to ask you
something, Angie.

225
00:18:57,667 --> 00:18:59,601
I'd like you to adopt my son.

226
00:19:01,638 --> 00:19:03,833
No, Lib, I can't do that.
Not to you.

227
00:19:03,907 --> 00:19:06,705
<i>I've thought it through. </i>

228
00:19:06,777 --> 00:19:10,713
I barely survived my parents' house.
I'm not gonna put him there.

229
00:19:13,183 --> 00:19:16,710
<i>Money won't be a problem
because there's the $2 million... </i>

230
00:19:16,787 --> 00:19:19,483
from the life insurance, and it's going
into a trust fund in his name.

231
00:19:19,556 --> 00:19:23,492
- It isn't about money.
- I know.

232
00:19:26,563 --> 00:19:30,158
Matty loves you.

233
00:19:32,135 --> 00:19:34,695
We can't let him become
a ward of the state.

234
00:19:48,585 --> 00:19:50,746
Thank you.

235
00:19:52,756 --> 00:19:54,747
Hey, kiddo.

236
00:19:54,825 --> 00:19:56,918
