- What a remarkable wrap.</i>

696
01:08:13,180 --> 01:08:15,045
Where on earth
did you find that?

697
01:08:15,115 --> 01:08:17,879
The first lady asked me the same thing
when we stayed at the White House...

698
01:08:17,951 --> 01:08:20,044
and I wouldn't
tell her either.

699
01:08:20,120 --> 01:08:22,054
<i>- Your invitation, sir?
- I got it right here.</i>

700
01:08:22,122 --> 01:08:24,716
<i>- Enjoy your evening. Good evening, miss.
- Good evening.</i>

701
01:09:25,685 --> 01:09:28,552
<i>- Good evening, mesdames and messieurs.
- Good evening!</i>

702
01:09:28,622 --> 01:09:30,647
We're delighted to have you
with us this evening...

703
01:09:30,724 --> 01:09:35,525
<i>on this very special occasion. As is the
custom in New Orleans, since before... </i>

704
01:09:35,595 --> 01:09:40,032
the War of Northern Aggression...

705
01:09:40,100 --> 01:09:42,398
We offer the ladies of this fair city
our first bachelor...

706
01:09:42,469 --> 01:09:46,906
to be put up on the auction block,
our host, Jonathan Devereaux.

707
01:09:51,278 --> 01:09:54,304
<i>Where is that man?
Where is that man?</i>

708
01:09:55,282 --> 01:09:57,216
<i>- Hey, Jonathan.
- Thank you, Louis.</i>

709
01:09:58,251 --> 01:10:00,185
You all having a good time?

710
01:10:01,721 --> 01:10:04,747
<i>Now then, ladies,
what you see before you... </i>

711
01:10:04,825 --> 01:10:07,089
is a moderately presentable
man in his 30s...

712
01:10:07,160 --> 01:10:11,153
given to unhealthy thoughts
and a dissipated lifestyle...

713
01:10:12,499 --> 01:10:15,297
With... and this is what's gonna
cost you the really big money...

714
01:10:20,407 --> 01:10:22,875
Absolutely no
redeeming moral virtue.

715
01:10:26,113 --> 01:10:29,844
- Five hundred.
- Dear woman, my cuff links cost more.

716
01:10:29,916 --> 01:10:32,476
<i>Do I hear a thousand?</i>

717
01:10:32,552 --> 01:10:34,679
- A thousand.
- Thank you.

718
01:10:36,923 --> 01:10:40,188
- Mmm!
- Two thousand.

719
01:10:41,862 --> 01:10:44,194
<i>All right, now, did I just hear
the voice of the charming Miss Monroe?</i>

720
01:10:44,264 --> 01:10:47,233
<i>'Cause I was just starting to worry...
beginning to think you didn't care. </i>

721
01:10:47,300 --> 01:10:49,996
<i>Twenty-five hundred. </i>

722
01:10:53,306 --> 01:10:56,400
Twenty-five hundred.
We have a new bidder.

723
01:10:56,476 --> 01:10:59,036
- Twenty-five hundred.
- Three thousand.

724
01:11:00,247 --> 01:11:03,080
- Five thousand.
- Oh!

725
01:11:10,690 --> 01:11:13,022
Fifty-five hundred.

726
01:11:17,264 --> 01:11:20,597
We have fifty-five hundred.
Will, uh...

727
01:11:20,667 --> 01:11:22,601
Will the lady take us to six?

728
01:11:24,771 --> 01:11:28,263
Ten thousand dollars.

729
01:11:32,012 --> 01:11:35,812
<i>Well, see, at last,
someone who knows my true value. </i>

730
01:11:35,882 --> 01:11:38,715
<i>Now, Miss Monroe,
I believe the bid... </i>

731
01:11:38,785 --> 01:11:41,811
is to you at $10,500.

732
01:11:41,888 --> 01:11:43,879
Well, you can have him, honey.

733
01:11:43,957 --> 01:11:45,891
Believe me,
he ain't worth that much...

734
01:11:45,959 --> 01:11:47,927
I know from personal experience.

735
01:11:47,994 --> 01:11:50,292
Yeah. Thank you, honey.

736
01:11:50,363 --> 01:11:52,797
<i>All right, going once. </i>

737
01:11:52,866 --> 01:11:54,800
Going twice.

738
01:11:56,069 --> 01:11:59,232
Sold to the woman
in the back.

739
01:11:59,306 --> 01:12:01,240
Ten thousand dollars.

740
01:12:04,978 --> 01:12:07,640
Would you like to come forward
and claim your prize, young lady?

741
01:12:14,854 --> 01:12:17,254
Hello, Nick.

742
01:12:23,930 --> 01:12:25,864
Well, aren't you
gonna give me a kiss?

743
01:12:28,001 --> 01:12:30,469
I think I've earned it.

744
01:12:44,451 --> 01:12:47,887
<i>- And now...
- I'll make this real easy for you, Nick.</i>

745
01:12:47,954 --> 01:12:50,548
I'll make you an offer
you can't refuse.

746
01:12:50,624 --> 01:12:53,058
You used to love a good deal,
didn't you?

747
01:12:53,126 --> 01:12:55,390
- Can we take this someplace private?
- I don't think so.

748
01:12:55,462 --> 01:12:57,726
I remember what happened
the last time we were alone.

749
01:12:57,797 --> 01:13:00,231
I don't believe we've met.
I'm Suzanne Monroe.

750
01:13:00,300 --> 01:13:02,860
I'm Libby.
I'm his wife.

751
01:13:03,970 --> 01:13:06,029
Well, Jonathan!

752
01:13:06,106 --> 01:13:09,473
<i>A minute ago a bachelor,
and now you're married. </i>

753
01:13:09,542 --> 01:13:12,409
You don't waste any time.

754
01:13:12,479 --> 01:13:14,413
- You been in New Orleans long?
- She's, uh...

755
01:13:14,481 --> 01:13:16,415
I'm just passing through town
to pick up my child.

756
01:13:16,483 --> 01:13:18,417
- I'll be leaving very soon.
- How nice.

757
01:13:18,485 --> 01:13:20,385
<i>We're finally putting the past
behind us and moving on... </i>

758
01:13:20,453 --> 01:13:23,980
- with our lives, aren't we, Jonathan?
- Sure.

759
01:13:24,057 --> 01:13:25,991
I do have
one question, though.

760
01:13:26,059 --> 01:13:28,823
How long were Angie and you fucking
before you decided to get rid of me?

761
01:13:32,766 --> 01:13:35,669
- Would you excuse us, please?
- Oh, yeah, sure. Go ahead.

762
01:13:38,104 --> 01:13:40,038
- Where is he, Nick?
- Libby. Libby...

763
01:13:40,106 --> 01:13:42,040
You destroyed my life,
and I will destroy yours...

764
01:13:42,108 --> 01:13:44,042
unless you give me Matty.

765
01:13:44,110 --> 01:13:47,045
- That's all I want.
- Let me explain something to you.

766
01:13:47,113 --> 01:13:49,104
You have to understand something.
We were going under.

767
01:13:49,182 --> 01:13:51,548
We were gonna lose everything.

768
01:13:51,618 --> 01:13:54,519
If I'd had any guts,
I would have killed myself...

769
01:13:54,587 --> 01:13:56,521
but I was trying
to protect you.

770
01:13:56,589 --> 01:13:59,683
That's why I got the life insurance...
I would be out of the picture...

771
01:13:59,759 --> 01:14:02,387
and you and Matty
would be okay.

772
01:14:02,462 --> 01:14:05,522
And I-I just never believed
they would convict you.

773
01:14:06,966 --> 01:14:09,560
They did, Nick.

774
01:14:09,636 --> 01:14:12,764
And the thing with Angie
happened later.

775
01:14:12,839 --> 01:14:16,002
It was just...
It was a nightmare.

776
01:14:16,076 --> 01:14:18,408
And the worst part of it
was being away from you.

777
01:14:18,478 --> 01:14:21,106
So is that why
you killed her?

778
01:14:23,583 --> 01:14:26,882
- That was an accident.
- Nice try, Nick. I'm not buying.

779
01:14:26,953 --> 01:14:29,786
<i>- It's bullshit.
- I will swear on the life of our son.</i>

780
01:14:29,856 --> 01:14:33,223
Oh, don't you fucking dare.

781
01:14:33,293 --> 01:14:36,694
You can keep your hotel,
your fancy accent and your new name.

782
01:14:36,763 --> 01:14:39,254
- Just give me Matty.
- I understand.

783
01:14:39,332 --> 01:14:41,766
No. Now.
Give him to me now.

784
01:14:41,835 --> 01:14:43,769
Libby, it's the middle of the night.
I can't just walk away.

785
01:14:43,837 --> 01:14:45,634
<i>- Do you think I'm stupid?
- No, I don't think you're stupid.</i>

786
01:14:45,705 --> 01:14:48,936
- I won't let you slip away once again.
- It's too far to Matty's school.

787
01:14:49,008 --> 01:14:53,035
- You've got to be patient.
- I've been patient for six years.

788
01:14:53,113 --> 01:14:55,775
<i>-  Do I hear 2,000?
- I want my child.</i>

789
01:14:55,849 --> 01:14:58,841
Ah! Thank you.
You're a beautiful woman.

790
01:14:58,918 --> 01:15:02,581
I'll call you tomorrow, Nick.
No screwing around.

791
01:15:02,655 --> 01:15:05,419
<i>Going twice.
Okay, 2,000 for the lady in red. </i>

792
01:15:05,492 --> 01:15:09,053
Excuse me. Do you know
where Mr. Devereaux is?

793
01:15:09,129 --> 01:15:11,063
- He's at the bar, sir.
- Over here?

794
01:15:11,131 --> 01:15:13,065
- Yes, sir.
- Thank you.

795
01:15:13,133 --> 01:15:17,001
<i>You ready to spend some more money?
Who's gonna start us off?</i>

796
01:15:22,742 --> 01:15:25,210
I'm sorry.
Oh, thank you, Marcel.

797
01:15:25,278 --> 01:15:27,212
- Can I offer you a drink?
- Oh, no thanks.

798
01:15:27,280 --> 01:15:29,214
Wait a second.
Let me guess.

799
01:15:29,282 --> 01:15:31,512
I take you
for scotch and soda.

800
01:15:31,584 --> 01:15:34,178
Well, I'll have
a Diet Coke, please.

801
01:15:34,254 --> 01:15:37,018
Well, all right, but I bet you used
to drink and now you're on the wagon.

802
01:15:37,090 --> 01:15:40,025
- Ten dollars says I'm right.
- You've never seen this woman before?

803
01:15:40,093 --> 01:15:42,027
- No, I'm positive.
- Okay.

804
01:15:42,095 --> 01:15:44,359
Let me get it straight.
She believes that I am her husband...

805
01:15:44,430 --> 01:15:46,364
- Oh, yeah.
- Whom she killed.

806
01:15:46,432 --> 01:15:48,366
Yes, sir.

807
01:15:49,435 --> 01:15:51,369
That's-That's pretty far-fetched.

808
01:15:51,437 --> 01:15:53,371
Far-fetched or not,
she is in New Orleans...

809
01:15:53,439 --> 01:15:55,703
she does have a gun
and she is looking for you.

810
01:15:55,775 --> 01:15:59,142
- Thank you. I'll alert our security.
- You do that.

811
01:16:15,795 --> 01:16:18,059
Cops have been
passing these out.

812
01:16:22,168 --> 01:16:24,898
No reward. Screw 'em.

813
01:16:27,440 --> 01:16:30,432
You're gonna be posted
in every hotel in town.

814
01:16:30,510 --> 01:16:33,673
So much for a good night's sleep.

815
01:16:40,486 --> 01:16:44,115
Take this.
Get out of here.

816
01:16:47,961 --> 01:16:49,895
Thanks a lot.

817
01:17:25,999 --> 01:17:28,559
Let's go, Lehman.
We spotted your girl.

818
01:18:01,534 --> 01:18:03,468
Where'd she go, Dilbert?

819
01:18:10,410 --> 01:18:12,344
Hey!

820
01:18:24,290 --> 01:18:26,315
Hey!

821
01:18:31,364 --> 01:18:33,298
Hey!

822
01:18:57,890 --> 01:18:59,824
Hey!

823
01:19:01,828 --> 01:19:04,820
- Hey!
- I'm sorry.

824
01:19:04,897 --> 01:19:06,831
- What do you think you're doing?
- I'm very sorry, ma'am.

825
01:19:06,899 --> 01:19:09,868
I thought you were somebody else.
It was a case of mistaken identity.

826
01:19:09,936 --> 01:19:13,531
- Have a good evening.
- I take it that ain't her.

827
01:19:27,785 --> 01:19:30,015
<i> Mr. Lehman. </i>

828
01:19:30,088 --> 01:19:31,680
Come in.

829
01:19:31,756 --> 01:19:34,224
<i>- Thank you.
- May I offer you a Cuban cigar?</i>

830
01:19:34,292 --> 01:19:36,556
Oh, no thanks.

831
01:19:36,628 --> 01:19:40,860
As you can see,
I'm alive and kicking.

832
01:19:40,932 --> 01:19:42,524
Yeah.

833
01:19:43,701 --> 01:19:45,635
So what can I do for you
this morning?

834
01:19:45,703 --> 01:19:48,536
We spotted the Parsons woman
in the Quarter last night.

835
01:19:48,606 --> 01:19:53,066
<i>She got away. I just came by
to find out if you'd heard from her. </i>

836
01:19:53,144 --> 01:19:56,113
<i>- Not a peep.
- Do you have any idea... </i>

837
01:19:56,181 --> 01:19:59,241
why she's fixated
her lunacy on you?

838
01:19:59,317 --> 01:20:01,308
Well, the world's
full of crazy people, am I right?

839
01:20:01,386 --> 01:20:03,411
Oh, yes, you are right.

840
01:20:03,488 --> 01:20:06,389
<i>Truer words
were never spoken. </i>

841
01:20:07,492 --> 01:20:10,586
Those are nice pictures there.

842
01:20:10,662 --> 01:20:12,755
Did your kids do them?

843
01:20:13,831 --> 01:20:16,698
Uh, no.

844
01:20:16,768 --> 01:20:20,226
Those pictures are by
a very great artist named Kandinsky.

845
01:20:20,305 --> 01:20:23,706
- Oh.
- Why do I think you already knew that?

846
01:20:26,778 --> 01:20:30,270
Excuse me for a second.

847
01:20:31,382 --> 01:20:34,180
Yes?

848
01:20:36,788 --> 01:20:40,087
- This is a business call.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

849
01:20:40,158 --> 01:20:42,251
I hope you'll excuse me.
You let yourself out that back door.

850
01:20:42,327 --> 01:20:45,819
<i>It leads to the kitchen. Get the chef
to fix you a New Orleans breakfast. </i>

851
01:20:45,897 --> 01:20:47,831
<i>- Thanks.
- I recommend the Eggs St. Jacques. </i>

852
01:20:47,899 --> 01:20:50,060
<i>- Oh, boy. That sounds good.
- Mm-hmm. I have your card. </i>

853
01:20:50,134 --> 01:20:52,762
Okay.

854
01:20:55,306 --> 01:20:58,036
Morning, darlin'.
I hope you had a nice night.

855
01:20:58,109 --> 01:21:02,546
I want you to bring Matty
to Lafayette Cemetery number three.

856
01:21:02,614 --> 01:21:05,549
A cemetery?
That's an odd choice for a reunion.

857
01:21:05,617 --> 01:21:09,178
It's a big tourist place, Nick.
Lot of people around.

858
01:21:09,254 --> 01:21:13,020
You're a smart girl.
I can have him there by 4:00.

859
01:21:53,431 --> 01:21:57,765
- Where's Matty?
- Relax. He's... He was nervous.

860
01:21:57,835 --> 01:22:00,702
So I just told him
he could go play inside.

861
01:22:08,313 --> 01:22:10,907
There he is.

862
01:22:10,982 --> 01:22:13,246
Matty?
Come over here, son.

863
01:22:14,319 --> 01:22:16,879
<i>Oh, geez. Matty... </i>

864
01:22:16,954 --> 01:22:19,184
- Okay, I'll get him for you.
- No! No.

865
01:22:20,258 --> 01:22:22,192
That's something
I want to do.

866
01:22:26,197 --> 01:22:27,926
<i>Matty?</i>

867
01:22:32,837 --> 01:22:35,567
Matty?

868
01:22:35,640 --> 01:22:37,938
<i>Hey, kiddo. </i>

869
01:22:40,878 --> 01:22:43,039
<i>Hey, Matty!</i>

870
01:23:39,170 --> 01:23:42,162
<i>Matty?</i>

871
01:23:42,240 --> 01:23:44,174
M- Matty, it's Mommy.

872
01:24:05,430 --> 01:24:09,366
<i> Mr. Lehman, you're gonna
have to learn to relax, son. </i>

873
01:24:09,434 --> 01:24:12,961
What have you got your panties
in such a twist about, anyhow?

874
01:24:14,572 --> 01:24:16,506
You ever arrest anybody...

875
01:24:16,574 --> 01:24:20,169
<i>- you thought was innocent, Mangold?
- Nope. </i>

876
01:24:24,282 --> 01:24:27,513
'Course there's no information
on Jonathan Devereaux...

877
01:24:27,585 --> 01:24:29,519
that's over three years old.

878
01:24:29,587 --> 01:24:32,681
- Three years ago the guy didn't exist.
- So he changed his name.

879
01:24:32,757 --> 01:24:34,691
Lots of folks
change their names, Lehman.

880
01:24:34,759 --> 01:24:36,693
- That don't make 'em criminals.
- Yeah, but I'm betting...

881
01:24:36,761 --> 01:24:39,195
he changed it from Simon Ryder,
and before that, Nick Parsons.

882
01:24:39,263 --> 01:24:42,255
- But you can't prove it.
- No.

883
01:25:10,428 --> 01:25:12,760
<i>Hey! Is that long distance?</i>

884
01:25:12,830 --> 01:25:14,991
Bill me.

885
01:25:15,066 --> 01:25:17,500
Lucy, hi.
This is Travis. Listen.

886
01:25:17,568 --> 01:25:20,628
I want you to get the D.M.V. To fax
me a Washington driver's license...

887
01:25:20,705 --> 01:25:22,696
photograph of one
Nicholas Parsons.

888
01:25:22,773 --> 01:25:24,707
I'm at the New Orleans
Police Department.

889
01:25:24,775 --> 01:25:26,709
<i>- You better talk to Mr. Carruthers.
- Travis!</i>

890
01:25:26,777 --> 01:25:30,679
<i>- His colon is twisted in a knot.
- Give me that.</i>

891
01:25:30,748 --> 01:25:32,978
I've had to cover
your office for you, Travis.

892
01:25:33,050 --> 01:25:35,041
- Where the hell are you?
- Listen to me, Karl.

893
01:25:35,119 --> 01:25:37,053
I think maybe this Parsons woman
has been telling the truth.

894
01:25:37,121 --> 01:25:39,055
You're not a law professor
anymore, Travis.

895
01:25:39,123 --> 01:25:41,057
You're barely even
a parole officer.

896
01:25:41,125 --> 01:25:44,322
<i>- So stop playing Mission Impossible...
- All I need...</i>

897
01:25:44,395 --> 01:25:47,031
is a D.M.V. Driver's license photograph
of Nicholas Parsons.

898
01:25:47,164 --> 01:25:49,189
You get back here today...

899
01:25:49,266 --> 01:25:51,757
because tomorrow, you're going
in front of the Commission.

900
01:25:51,835 --> 01:25:55,202
Karl, I know I'm right.

901
01:25:55,272 --> 01:25:57,536
You give me a chance, okay?

902
01:25:57,608 --> 01:25:59,542
Now, I'm asking you politely.

903
01:25:59,610 --> 01:26:02,044
You send me
the goddamn picture!

904
01:28:30,027 --> 01:28:31,961
Hey!

905
01:28:32,029 --> 01:28:34,998
<i> Hey!</i>

906
01:28:51,448 --> 01:28:53,109
It's not him.

907
01:28:53,183 --> 01:28:55,481
<i>See, Lehman, the thing is,
every now and again... </i>

908
01:28:55,552 --> 01:28:57,486
we all want to believe
in something...

909
01:28:57,554 --> 01:29:00,489
but we just keep forgetting
that 99.9 percent of the time...

910
01:29:00,557 --> 01:29:02,923
<i>life just flat don't work out. </i>

911
01:29:02,993 --> 01:29:04,927
I hadn't thought
of that, Mangold.

912
01:29:04,995 --> 01:29:08,328
- Thanks. I feel a lot better now.
- Any time, Hoss. Any time.

913
01:29:18,875 --> 01:29:21,537
Hold it.
Hold it right here.

914
01:29:49,473 --> 01:29:51,566
It's over, Libby.

915
01:29:51,641 --> 01:29:54,735
Oh, Travis.

916
01:30:22,772 --> 01:30:24,706
Messages.

917
01:30:25,942 --> 01:30:28,376
Thank you.

918
01:30:28,445 --> 01:30:31,539
<i>- Mr. Devereaux?
- Mr. Lehman.</i>

919
01:30:31,615 --> 01:30:33,708
<i>I'm sorry.
This is really not a good time. </i>

920
01:30:33,783 --> 01:30:35,717
I understand.

921
01:30:35,785 --> 01:30:38,219
A lot of people feel that way about me.
But I have good news.

922
01:30:38,288 --> 01:30:42,850
- Mm-hmm?
- Won't take long.

923
01:30:46,296 --> 01:30:49,561
- Well?
- Well...

924
01:30:49,633 --> 01:30:52,727
turns out I owe you
an apology, Mr. Devereaux.

925
01:30:54,304 --> 01:30:56,738
After our last conversation
I started thinking...

926
01:30:56,806 --> 01:31:00,242
maybe that Parsons woman is telling
the truth about who you used to be.

927
01:31:00,310 --> 01:31:04,747
So I asked the Washington
State Department of Motor Vehicles...

928
01:31:04,814 --> 01:31:09,649
to send me a driver's license
photograph of Nicholas Parsons.

929
01:31:10,987 --> 01:31:13,751
- And?
- And this is what came up.

930
01:31:23,300 --> 01:31:25,234
Well...

931
01:31:26,937 --> 01:31:29,201
We all make mistakes.
There's no harm done.

932
01:31:29,272 --> 01:31:32,264
<i>Then I thought about it some more, and
it occurred to me what a common name... </i>

933
01:31:32,342 --> 01:31:34,276
Nicholas Parsons is.

934
01:31:34,344 --> 01:31:36,608
You know, it turns out
there were six.

935
01:31:36,680 --> 01:31:38,614
<i>And this... </i>

936
01:31:38,682 --> 01:31:41,242
<i>was number three. </i>

937
01:31:44,120 --> 01:31:46,418
I never liked that picture.

938
01:31:49,459 --> 01:31:52,223
So, Mr. Lehman,
you came here to make a deal...

939
01:31:52,295 --> 01:31:54,559
otherwise, I guess you would have
gone straight to the police.

940
01:31:54,631 --> 01:31:58,226
- So, question is, what's your price?
- A million dollars.

941
01:31:59,469 --> 01:32:02,563
It's a nice round figure, right?

942
01:32:02,639 --> 01:32:04,573
Uh...

943
01:32:07,143 --> 01:32:10,237
All right. But you're gonna have to
give me a couple of days.

944
01:32:10,313 --> 01:32:13,248
No way.
One million dollars, right now.

945
01:32:13,316 --> 01:32:17,013
Mr. Lehman, it's 9:00 at night.
I can't just...

946
01:32:21,024 --> 01:32:23,822
<i>Wait a minute.
Wait a minute. Wait. </i>

947
01:32:24,928 --> 01:32:27,658
I have $100,000
in the safe here.

948
01:32:27,731 --> 01:32:30,461
And you can have that now.

949
01:32:30,634 --> 01:32:32,568
I'll get you the rest tomorrow.

950
01:32:33,737 --> 01:32:35,671
You got a deal.

951
01:32:38,041 --> 01:32:40,976
We do have one other problem,
and that's Mrs. Parsons.

952
01:32:41,044 --> 01:32:43,877
<i>She could still make a lot of trouble
for us, even from prison... </i>

953
01:32:43,947 --> 01:32:46,711
- and I really don't need that.
- I think I've solved that problem.

954
01:32:46,783 --> 01:32:50,184
- What do you mean?
- Let's say the problem has been buried.

955
01:32:50,253 --> 01:32:53,654
- Really?
- She's gone, I promise you.

956
01:33:04,301 --> 01:33:06,394
You're not very good
at keeping promises, Nick.

957
01:33:06,469 --> 01:33:09,165
You gonna do something?

958
01:33:09,239 --> 01:33:11,207
What are you talking to me for?
She's the one with the gun.

959
01:33:19,683 --> 01:33:22,675
<i>They're tough in Louisiana, Libby. </i>

960
01:33:22,752 --> 01:33:25,277
You shoot me,
they'll give you the gas chamber.

961
01:33:25,355 --> 01:33:27,516
No, they won't.

962
01:33:27,590 --> 01:33:30,684
It's called double jeopardy.
I learned a few things in prison, Nick.

963
01:33:30,760 --> 01:33:33,854
<i>I could shoot you in the middle
of Mardi Gras and they can't touch me. </i>

964
01:33:33,930 --> 01:33:36,694
<i>As an ex-law professor,
I can assure you she is right. </i>

965
01:33:40,937 --> 01:33:43,064
Where's my son?

966
01:33:44,941 --> 01:33:47,705
In St. Albans School
in Georgia, all right?

967
01:33:49,446 --> 01:33:51,641
You have your son back.
You got what you want.

968
01:34:02,292 --> 01:34:05,056
I haven't felt that good
in six years.

969
01:34:07,464 --> 01:34:09,557
I don't want to kill you, Nick.

970
01:34:09,632 --> 01:34:11,827
I just want you to suffer
like I suffered.

971
01:34:11,901 --> 01:34:14,426
<i>What she means, Nick, is,
you're going to prison... </i>

972
01:34:14,504 --> 01:34:16,734
for murder.

973
01:34:16,806 --> 01:34:19,172
- Who did I supposedly murder?
- Me.

974
01:34:23,079 --> 01:34:25,980
<i>- All you've got is an old fax photo.
- Which supplies the motive. </i>

975
01:34:26,049 --> 01:34:28,517
Your wife, whom you had framed,
tracks you down...

976
01:34:28,585 --> 01:34:31,349
and to keep her from exposing you,
you kill her.

977
01:34:31,421 --> 01:34:34,015
You won't get away with it.

978
01:34:34,090 --> 01:34:36,149
Well, I think
I've solved that problem.

979
01:34:36,226 --> 01:34:38,854
<i>- What do you mean?
- Let's say the problem has been buried. </i>

980
01:34:38,928 --> 01:34:41,829
<i>- Really?
- She's gone, I promise you. </i>

981
01:34:43,900 --> 01:34:46,698
Taped confessions are
very persuasive in court, Nick...

982
01:34:46,770 --> 01:34:48,704
<i>and of course there is... </i>

983
01:34:48,772 --> 01:34:51,832
the physical evidence that we're gonna
put in the trunk of your car.

984
01:34:51,908 --> 01:34:54,877
<i>A shovel, hair, my fingerprints,
a little blood. </i>

985
01:34:54,944 --> 01:34:57,845
<i>- Don't forget the gasoline.
- It'll look like you burned... </i>

986
01:34:57,914 --> 01:35:01,042
and buried my body
just like you say on the tape.

987
01:35:01,117 --> 01:35:04,348
The prosecution rests.
You better get out of here.

988
01:35:04,421 --> 01:35:06,389
<i>Nobody wants a dead woman
walking around when the police... </i>

989
01:35:06,456 --> 01:35:09,892
<i>are trying to arrest a guy
for her murder. </i>

990
01:35:09,959 --> 01:35:12,359
Wait a minute.
I'll take that gun.

991
01:36:32,141 --> 01:36:34,609
Well, Lehman, you gonna live?

992
01:36:37,313 --> 01:36:39,304
I doubt it.

993
01:36:39,382 --> 01:36:41,976
Ms. Parsons, since you are
still legally his wife...

994
01:36:42,051 --> 01:36:45,248
I expect you just inherited yourself
a right fine little hotel here.

995
01:36:45,321 --> 01:36:48,085
Not interested.

996
01:36:55,631 --> 01:36:57,599
I guess I'm gonna
take off now.

997
01:36:57,666 --> 01:37:02,933
No. No, you're not. You're a parole
violator. You're in my c-custody.

998
01:37:03,005 --> 01:37:06,270
You're going with me to Seattle...

999
01:37:06,342 --> 01:37:09,937
where I will demand
a full pardon and a parade...

1000
01:37:10,012 --> 01:37:12,310
and a little pink poodle...

1001
01:37:13,382 --> 01:37:15,247
on a key chain.

1002
01:37:26,562 --> 01:37:28,496
<i>Come on, Ryan, pass it!</i>

1003
01:37:43,813 --> 01:37:47,715
What are you waiting for?
Go on.

1004
01:37:50,152 --> 01:37:54,919
I don't know if I've ever been
so scared in my whole life.

1005
01:37:54,990 --> 01:37:57,925
I think a big part of me
never thought I'd really find him.

1006
01:38:00,663 --> 01:38:03,757
What if he doesn't recognize me?

1007
01:38:03,833 --> 01:38:06,131
- I mean, maybe after all this time...
- Damn, woman!

1008
01:38:06,202 --> 01:38:09,603
Because of you, I have lost a perfectly
good used car, and a not-so-good job.

1009
01:38:09,672 --> 01:38:11,970
If you don't go to this kid
right now...

1010
01:38:12,041 --> 01:38:14,475
I'm gonna have you
arrested for stupidity.

1011
01:38:14,543 --> 01:38:16,477
Go on.

1012
01:38:20,950 --> 01:38:22,884
Thanks, Lehman.

1013
01:38:23,953 --> 01:38:25,887
You saved my life.

1014
01:38:29,959 --> 01:38:32,257
You saved mine too.

1015
01:38:45,307 --> 01:38:48,743
- Coach Matthews. How you doing?
- Nice to meet you.

1016
01:38:48,811 --> 01:38:51,245
It'll be halftime soon.

1017
01:39:06,462 --> 01:39:09,295
Halftime!

1018
01:39:09,365 --> 01:39:11,560
Matty.

1019
01:39:12,434 --> 01:39:14,459
Matty.

1020
01:39:28,684 --> 01:39:31,380
Hi.

1021
01:39:34,323 --> 01:39:36,257
Do you know who I am?

1022
01:39:38,861 --> 01:39:40,795
They told me
you were dead.

1023
01:39:43,465 --> 01:39:45,399
No, sweetheart.

